title: Excitation functions of reactions of 7 to 24 MeV He-3 ions with Cu-63 and Cu-65

x4freetext: Excitation functions of reactions of 7 to 24 MeV He-3
ions with Cu-63 and Cu-65

x4codes.hlp: Los Alamos National Laboratory, NM, United States of America
Los Alamos National Laboratory, NM, United States of America

x4freetext: Stacks were bombarded at beam energy settings of 12 and
24 MeV. In general cross sections from the 12 MeV beam
agreed with the low energy cross sections from the
24 MeV bombardments and should have uncertainties
not greater than 0.25 MeV.
The energies of the particles were determined
before and after each bombardment by exposure
emulsion plates to particles scattered out of the beam
by an Au-foil. The energy calibration was taken from
J.J.Wilkins,Aere-G/R664(1951) and were known to 0.15
MeV. Additional measurements with a solid state
detector for 25 MeV He3 and 15 MeV alphas agreed
within 0.1 MeV.
The energy degradation in the stacks were calculated
by range-energy values which were derived from
H.Bichsel et al.,Phys.Rev.105,1788(1957)
H.Bichsel,Phys.Rev.112,1089(1958)
L.C.Northcliffe,Phys.Rev.120,1744(1960)
P.E.Schambra et al.,Phys.Rev.120,1758(1960).
The values used are listed in Tab.2 of the publication.
Corrections for recoil effects (about 1% at 10 MeV,
3% at 24 MeV) were limited to the first Cu-foil and the
Cu-foil immediately following an Al-foil in a stack,
Because for such foils there is no influx of recoil
products to compensate for recoil losses.
Lapf
Some corrections have been included by
CAJAD
Some reaction lines are corrected. The
comments for decay-data are included.
Subent 011 was deleted, according N.Otsuka
comment.All subentries were corrected according new
rules.
Foils of electrolytic natural Cu, thickness 0.00025
inch, individually weighed. Some of the stacks
contained single Al-foils for measurement of recoil
losses.
* By CAJAD*. According to ENSDF positron intensities
are different from used by authors.
Detection efficiency and sample thickness corrections
were computed by the method of Bayhurst and Prestwood,
Nucleonics,17,No.3,82(1959).

x4freetext: Cross Sections for the Production of Ga-65 are due to
the reaction Cu-63(HE3,N) at low energies. At high
energies they were extrapolated with an energy
dependence derived from the Cu-65(HE3,N)Ga-67
excitation function.
Foils of Electrolytic Natural Cu, Thickness 0.00025
Inch, Individually Weighed. Some of the Stacks
Contained Single Al-Foils For Measurement of Recoil
Losses.
- By CAJAD - According to ENSDF Positron Intensities
Are Different from Used by Authors.
Detection Efficiency and Sample Thickness Corrections
Were Computed by the Method of Bayhurst and Prestwood,
Nucleonics,17,No.3,82(1959).
The Computed Detection Efficiencies For Zn-65 and
Ga-65 were Cross-Checked by Counting Samples
Prepared from a Strong Reference Solution of Ga-65.
An Apparent 4% Difference was Compromised by
Arbitrarily Lowering the Efficiency of Zn-65 by 2% and
Raising That of Ga-65 by an Equal Amount.
The Energy Dependency of the Cu-65(HE3,N) Cross
Sections was Used to Estimate the Cu-63(HE3,N) Cross
Sections Above 14 MeV.
